PLANTation from Origin Magazine with Maranda Pleasant. MP: What is it that you are most proud of in your life? The one thing that you are most proud of bringing to this planet? Robert: “Beautiful children. They are a reflection of the love that you put into them. They have a great resonance and they’re spectacular. All three of them have got a great beat. I wouldn’t say that they understand me but at least they are supportive. There’s a great mutuality and I’m really proud of that. In the middle of everything that I’ve done as a singer or as somebody who’s jumped on top of a few old books and turned ‘em into songs about hobbits f*cking vikings, I think I’ve danced a beautiful dance through it all, without becoming too much of a cliche. I’ve enjoyed the two-step. It’s brought me great gifts. When I sit back there with my driver’s hat on and I look at my passenger, I think, Well, this ain’t so bad.”
#RobertPlant #OriginMagazine #UK #Children #Hobbits

2018 PLANTation from Interview for American Songwriter by Stephen Deusner. Here’s the snippet: Instead, he’d rather keep tinkering and experimenting. “After John [Bonham] passed away in 1981, I did my first solo album, Pictures At Eleven,” he recalls. “I had the first Roland drum machine, which was before the TR808. I wrote a track called ‘Fat Lip’ with it and thought I’d died and gone to heaven. I thought, I’ve made it! I’ve slipped right the way through all that stuff that went on forever and ever, and here I am singing into a drumbox, which is about twelve inches cubed. It’s not very sexy, I must say in comparison to John Bonham. But I thought it was great. I dived into every single techno moment on my solo records, much to the horror of the hard-rock fans who were expecting, you know …” He pauses to find the most diplomatic phrase. “… something else to happen.” Over the 35 years since he released Pictures At Eleven, Plant has been avoiding that something else, chasing his own obsessions rather than revisit the glory days and beloved back catalog of his old band.
#RobertPlant #PicturesAtEleven #AmericanSongwriterMagazine

LED ZEPPELIN II
RELEASE DATE: October 22, 1969. Recorded at various studios in the UK and North America.  TRACKS: Side 1: Whole Lotta Love / What Is And What Should Never Be / The Lemon Song / Thank You Side 2: Heartbreaker Living Loving Maid (She's Just A Woman)/ Ramble On/ Bring It On Home. Certified 12x Multi-Platinum on November 15, 1999. Certified 11x Multi-Platinum on March 29, 1999. Certified  8x Multi-Platinum on November 25, 1997. Certified 6x Multi-Platinum on August 11, 1992. Certified 5x Multi-Platinum on December 11, 1990. Certified Platinum on December 11, 1990. Certified Gold on November 10, 1969. SINGLES: 11/7/1969 - Whole Lotta Love/Living Loving Maid (She’s Just A Woman).
COINCIDING TOURS: European Tour Autumn 1969: Started October 3, 1969 at the Circus Theatre in Scheveningen, Netherlands and ended October 12, 1969 at the Lyceum Ballroom in London, England. North American Tour Autumn 1969: Started October 17, 1969 at Carnegie Hall in New York, New York and ended November 8, 1969 at the Winterland Ballroom in San Francisco, California. FUN FACT: Led Zeppelin II was nicknamed ‘The Brown Bomber’ in reference to the sepia tinted cover, the depiction of the bombing squadron, the silhouette of the Zeppelin airship and, most importantly, the explosive music contained within. The group of men on the front cover is a photograph of the Jasta Division of the German airforce with the band members faces inserted in place of those of the pilots. The faces of Peter Grant and Richard Cole were also added. The woman in the picture is Glynis Johns, the mother from "Mary Poppins". Her presence in the photo is an obvious play on the name of recording engineer Glyn Johns. The other face added was that of bluesman Blind Willie Johnson. 
#LedZeppelinII #JimmyPage #RobertPlant #JohnBonham #JohnPaulJones

2014 PLANTation from Vice Magazine interview. ERIC: “How do you feel on stage now versus ten, 20, 30 years ago?”ROBERT: “I have no idea of the comparison, of course, because it's an existentialist gig to be the frontman, the sharp end of a band. So maybe I'm probably more reckless now, because I was learning the game all the way through - still am, really. And you're new to what you do, the concept of the machinery of your gig is new, and it's resonating in a new world. But music doesn't go away. It just morphs and morphs. What I was doing was almost animal in the beginning; I was mimicking, borrowing, stealing, and creating a personality physically, visually, and musically. I don't know if it was good or bad; it's just what I did when I was your age.”
#RobertPlantOnAging #LedZeppelin

PLANTation from the S.F. Chronicle in September 2019. Here’s the snippet - Q: People would have loved for you to just keep making records with Alison Krauss and picking up Grammy Awards. Are you trying to satisfy your curiosity, or are you just a completely restless person and would probably be medicated if you were born in a different time? ROBERT: “Well, I do self-medicate now by just doing something that’s really full of heart. And the Space Shifters and the Band of Joy was full of heart. And “Raising Sand” was full of heart. I’ve always been the singer in a group, and to share the front with two of the most remarkable female singers was just a privilege. But they have to go do other stuff. I can’t take anybody else with me to the pre-Sahara or Zagora in Morocco or somewhere like that, so I got to go my own. That’s how it works. It’s all just a natural process. I mean, it’s marvelous if you can stay with one thing for like, 20 or 30 years. As long as that satisfies, that’s fantastic. There’s still a lot of stuff that I haven’t been able to do. I don’t even know what it is yet, but I will.” (Full interview on my website in bio area under “2019+ Talk - “Robert Plant: Hardly Strictly Bluegrass - SF Chronicle 9/28/19”.)
#selfMedication #WearingAndTearing #PattiGriffin #RaisingSand #RobertPlant

March 2018 “PLANTation with Esquire Magazine. JEFF: But surely there’s a lot of money to be made by reuniting with Led Zeppelin, especially in the corporatized world we live in.” Robert: Look, if substance was of no value, or of no significance, then I wouldn't be trying to do anything. But I believe it is, so this is what I do and all this talk about this or that or the other - you know, selling out the Mojave Desert - it so archaic. It's just such a ridiculous criteria by which to be judged. When you've been there, like me, and you know how shatteringly insular everything becomes, it makes my relationship with this carnival I’m with currently priceless. But to try and make it something to fit in with the a symbol of success just for the hell of it, or to go back to try to relive the glory days, I don't think that's really where I'm at at this time in my life.
But as for what I’ll be doing in five years time, I haven't got the answer. I haven't got a clue. Full interview is on my website under “2019+ Talk - ESQUIRE MAGAZINE - 03/02/2018
Is Tired of Answering the Obvious Question”
#RobertPlant #ZeppelinReunions #EsquireMagazine

2014 PLANTation from Vice Magazine Interview (Full interview is on my website under “2019+ Talk - Vice Magazine - 10/02/2014
Robert Plant's Good, Big Life”) ERIC: “Are you still looking at the exit sign?” ROBERT: “Yes. I'm looking at the number of people who get up to get popcorn when I sing a song they don't know.” ERIC: “Is that an obstacle in your career that you've felt at all, people expected something?” ROBERT: “I haven't got a career. This is the permanent vacation that Aerosmith sang about. You know? What more could I wish for? Look where I'm at. I haven't even had a nap yet today; it's fantastic. And no stimulants, nothing at all. [Points to the apartment building next to the hotel] Somebody got a green garden on the 38th floor there, and I'm not in it. I'm not taking care of some guy's garden. This is not a career. This is some sort of an award.”
#RobertPlant #Aerosmith #MusicCareers #LedZeppelin #ViceMagazine

In 2010, Robert was being interviewed by Steve Austin for A.V. Club newspaper. He was being asked if Robert was surprised about the success of 'Raising Sand' and the above qoute was part of the reply. He went on to say - "There’s a huge, huge group of people my age from my village back on the Welsh border who are bereft of music that makes sense to them. And there are less and less avenues of access. And so if something is strong and it can creep into the public eye, or the public ear, whisper in the ear, it re-invokes hope in people my age because there’s so little access to stuff. Because I’d been offered two amazing songs that I’d never heard and for me to sing. And I didn’t know I could do that. And I did it and fled. Just in case it didn’t really happen… I just couldn’t believe I’d gone from “The Lemon Song” to that." #RaisingSand #AllisonKrauss #diversity #age #robertplant #rockgod #rockvocalist

NINE LIVES - BOXED SET
RELEASE DATE: November 21, 2006
Nine Lives is a box set of Robert Plant's  solo work. It includes remastered and  expanded editions of nine albums with unreleased tracks and b-sides and a  DVD. 
The DVD has 20 music videos, live performance footage, and a  career-spanning interview with Plant, as well as interviews with friends  including drummer Phil Collins, Who lead singer Roger Daltrey, singer-songwriter Tori Amos, tennis star John McEnroe, and former Atlantic Records President Ahmet Ertegun, among others. 
The albums are: 
Pictures at Eleven
The Principle of Moments
The Honeydrippers: Volume One
Shaken 'n' Stirred
Now and Zen
Manic Nirvana
Fate of Nations
Dreamland
Mighty ReArranger
#NineLivesRobertPlant

Pagetation from 2020 interview with Esquire Magazine. Jimmy was being asked about his new anthology book - Alan: Mostly, The Anthology illustrates the tale of a boy whose family moved into a house where the previous owners had left a guitar, an accident that set him on a lifelong quest. Jimmy: “The guitar made an intervention into my life, that’s  the way I see it,” he says. “And then I became totally obsessed - the guitar just became another limb, like it was grafted on.” Along the way, Page’s text covers moments like acquiring a sitar in 1962, years before George Harrison discovered Indian music, or playing sessions with Nico and checking out the Velvet Underground in a New York nightclub (“They were incredible,” he says, “I could never work out why people weren’t going to see them”).
